w yourself" functions not only as a command to speak and listen, but also as a call to action and feeling. The book argues that poetic modes of knowing - though central to poetry understood as a genre - are also at the root of any conscious effort to move beyond the subjective limits of language and selfhood in the hopes of touching upon the unknown. Engaging and erudite, The Poetic Imperative is an invitation to direct our attention simultaneously to the finite and embodied limits of selfhood, as well as to what those limits touch: the infinite, the Other, and truth itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPoetics. 0aPoetry, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aSelf in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800305240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228003052423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228003052/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles